      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so if there's like a delay or if a bank accidentally holds the funds too long, what happens? is there a way to make sure the money doesn't just sit there forever or get lost in the system?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great question! Delays can happen, and it's important to have safeguards in place. Typically, the escrow agreement will outline the terms and conditions, including how long the funds can be held before being released. If there's a delay, the escrow agent should communicate with both parties to explain the situation and provide an estimated timeline for when the funds will be released.\n\nIf a bank or escrow company accidentally holds the funds too long, there are usually provisions in the escrow agreement that allow for interest to be paid on the held funds, or for the bank to compensate the parties for the delay. It's also a good idea to regularly check in with the escrow agent to stay updated on the status of your funds.\n\nIn the rare event that the funds are lost or mishandled, there may be legal recourse available to recover the money. It's important to work with a reputable escrow agent and to have a clear understanding of the terms of the escrow agreement to protect your interests. If you're ever unsure or concerned about the handling of your funds, don't hesitate to reach out to the escrow agent or seek legal advice.",
